Born2Root

Target IP: 192.168.183.49

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above: SSH, HTTP, RPC, and another RPC.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Are those possible usernames for this machine? The Contact Us section is interesting as only martin is there.


From the nmap scan above, there is a robots.txt file with two entries: /wordpress-blog and /files. The /files directory is empty. And the /wordpress-blog is not helpful. Time to perform directory search.


While performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.183.49/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt, I found an interesting directory called /icons.



This /icons directory contains a file called VDSoyuAXiO.txt. And this text file contains SSH key? I downloaded this key to my local machine, changed the permission to 600, and used the command ssh -i id_rsa martin@192.168.183.49 -o 'PubkeyAcceptedKeyTypes +ssh-rsa' to gain access to SSH.

Exploitation


And now I have a foothold on the machine as martin. When logged in, it asks for the "secret" password. I input secret and I gained access.

Privilege Escalation


The .bashrc file contains the string above. Is there a Python script?


Interesting cronjob which is owned by the user jimmy. Trying to transfer pspy is not allowed either :(.

I created the sekurity.py file with the Python reverse shell script as shown above. Then I changed the file permission to be executable, and started a listener on port 8444.


After waiting for some time, I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8444.


There is an interesting binary /home/jimmy/networker with SUID bit set.

Running strings on this binary shows the juicy details above. I tried creating a malicious echo binary but it did not work. I did not find anything else that is useful. There is one final user left: hadi. I only have one option left now: bruteforce the SSH application as hadi. Using rockyou.txt would be impossible; therefore, I filtered the possible passwords that has this user's name using the command cat /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt | grep hadi > hadi.txt.



And this worked!! The user hadi uses the password hadi123 for SSH. After many enumeration, I was stuck.


Trying to swtich user to root using this password worked. Now I have a root shell using the password hadi123.
